'''''Wizards & Warriors''''', titled '''''{{nihongo|Densetsu no Kishi Elrond|伝説の騎士エルロンド|''Legendary Knight Elrond''}}''''' in Japan, is an [[Action game|action]] [[platform game|platform]] video game developed by [[Rare (company)|Rare]] and published by [[Acclaim Entertainment]] for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]]. It was released in North America in December 1987, and in Europe on January 7, 1990. The player controls Kuros, "Knight Warrior of the ''Books of Excalibur''", as he sets out in the Kingdom of Elrond to defeat the evil wizard Malkil. Malkil holds the princess of Elrond captive in Castle IronSpire, deep within the forests of Elrond. The player fights through forests, tunnels, and caves, while collecting keys, treasure, weapons, and magic items.

It is Acclaim's first game as the domestic publisher, and Rare's second NES game, after ''[[Slalom (video game)|Slalom]]'' (1987). In the months surrounding its North American and European releases, ''Wizards & Warriors'' was featured in several video game magazines, including ''[[Nintendo Fun Club News]]'', ''[[Nintendo Power]]'', and ''[[VideoGames & Computer Entertainment]]''. It was praised for its graphics, sound, difficulty, and arcade-style gameplay. In 2010, ''[[Retro Gamer]]'' called it "a unique experience for NES gamers in 1987" that was "technically well ahead of other games for the console at the time", but attributed its relatively low difficulty to allowing unlimited [[continue (video gaming)|continue]]s without penalty.<ref name="RG" /> ''Wizards & Warriors'' was followed by three sequels: ''[[Ironsword: Wizards & Warriors&nbsp;II]]'' (1989), ''[[Wizards & Warriors&nbsp;X: The Fortress of Fear]]'' (1990), and ''[[Wizards & Warriors&nbsp;III: Kuros: Visions of Power]]'' (1992).

==Gameplay==
''Wizards & Warriors'' is a [[platform game]] in which players control Kuros through the forests of Elrond to Castle IronSpire, where he must defeat Malkil and rescue the princess.<ref name="Manual34">[[#manual|Instruction Manual]], pp. 3–4.</ref> Starting in the Elrond forest, players explore the trees to find items and to reach the caves and tunnels. There, various magical items and treasure are collected, and then caves filled with ice and lava are explored. Players fight through a second set of forests, and arrive at Castle IronSpire. It consists of a series of mazes in which players must use keys to open doors and possibly rescue other damsels. At the end lies the final confrontation with the wizard Malkil.<ref name="Manual57">[[#manual|Instruction Manual]], pp. 5–7.</ref>

[[File:Wizards & Warriors.png|thumb|left|Kuros is about to obtain the red key, to open the red treasure chest below.]]
Players use the control pad to move horizontally and to crouch. Kuros can attack enemies by using his Brightsword or with other weapons and magic.<ref name="Manual10">[[#manual|Instruction Manual]], p. 10.</ref> He can attack enemies while in the air or while standing by holding the sword in position.<ref name="RG" /> The objective of the game is to collect the various weapons, magic, gems, and treasure to overcome the enemies and other obstacles and hazards. Gems are required to bribe the creature who guards the entrance to the next level.<ref name="Manual78">[[#manual|Instruction Manual]], pp. 7–8.</ref><ref name="Manual1217">[[#manual|Instruction Manual]], pp. 12–17.</ref> At the end of each level is a [[boss (video gaming)|boss]] creature that has been empowered by Malkil's black magic. Bosses have an "Enemy's Black Magic Power" meter that shows how difficult the boss is, how many hits are required to defeat it, and what type of weaponry needs to be used.<ref name="FunClub">{{cite magazine |last=Reviewee |first=Louie |title=''Wizards & Warriors'' | magazine=[[Nintendo Fun Club News]] |issue=7 |date=June–July 1988 |pages=8–9}}</ref> Kuros has a [[Health (gaming)|life meter]] that decreases as time passes and when he sustains damage from enemies. Players loses a life when Kuros's life meter runs out, but keep all items. The [[game over|game ends]] when all three lives have been lost, but may [[continue (video gaming)|continue]]; upon continuing, all items remain, but the score is reset to zero. Kuros's life meter is replenished by collecting pieces of meat scattered throughout the levels.<ref name="Manual1718">[[#manual|Instruction Manual]], pp. 17–18.</ref>

Helpful items are inside acorns, torches, and treasure chests. Chests and doors are color-coded and require a key of matching color.<ref name="FunClub" /> Some weapons and magic items are replaced upon collecting a new item. Items include the following: "Boots of Force" that can kick open chests and doors; magical potions that temporarily grant Kuros invulnerability, extra speed, or extra jumping ability; gems to help bribe the end-of-level guardian; a shield to protect from enemy attacks; the "Potion of Levitation" that allows Kuros to float upward; the "Dagger of Throwing" and the "Battle Axe of Agor" that are thrown at enemies and return like a [[boomerang]]; the "Feather of Feather Fall" that slows Kuros's falling speed; the "Wand of Wonder" and "Staff of Power" that shoot out balls of ice and fire, respectively; the "Cloak of Darkness" that makes Kuros invisible to enemies; the "Boots of Lava Walk" that allows Kuros to walk on the lava; "Exploding Eggs" that destroys all on-screen enemies; "Alarm Clocks" that stop all enemies for a brief period; knife and axe upgrades; and a "horn" (trumpet) to reveal hidden doors to gem caves. Score increases include coins, orbs, chalices, entire hoards of treasure, and rescuing the damsels.<ref name="Manual1217" />

==Plot==
''Wizards & Warriors'' pits the hero Kuros, the "Knight Warrior of the ''Books of Excalibur''",<ref name="FunClub" /> against the main antagonist, the evil wizard Malkil. He was considered one of the greatest wizards in the land, such that [[Merlin]] was one of his students. However, the aging Malkil has gone mad, using his magic for evil, and has captured the princess as prisoner in Castle IronSpire, deep within the forests of Elrond. The brave knight Kuros, is summoned to venture through the forests of Elrond. He is armed with the legendary Brightsword, a sword that is powerful enough to beat demons, insects, undead, and the other creatures under Malkil's spell.<ref>[[#manual|Instruction Manual]], p. 2.</ref> With the sword, he ventures out through the forests of Elrond and the various caves and tunnels and to Castle IronSpire, to defeat Malkil and rescue the princess.<ref>[[#manual|Instruction Manual]], p. 5.</ref>

==Development==
''Wizards & Warriors'' was developed by the UK-based [[Rare (company)|Rare]] for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]].<ref name="RG">{{cite magazine |title=The History of ''Wizards & Warriors'' | magazine=[[Retro Gamer]] |publisher=[[Imagine Publishing]] |location=[[Bournemouth]] |issue=81 |date=September 2010 |pages=54–59 |issn=1742-3155 |oclc=489477015}}</ref> It was released by [[Acclaim Entertainment]] in North America in December&nbsp;1987;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nintendo.com/consumer/gameslist/manuals/nes_games.pdf|title=NES Games|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|access-date=July 17, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070317023021/http://nintendo.com/doc/nes_games.pdf|archive-date=March 17, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> and in Europe on January&nbsp;7, 1990. It was released in Japan by [[Jaleco]] with the title {{nihongo|''Densetsu no Kishi Elrond''|伝説の騎士エルロンド| ''Legendary Knight Elrond''}} on July&nbsp;15, 1988.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Wizards & Warriors'' Release Information for NES |website=[[GameFAQs]] |access-date=February 4, 2011 |url=http://www.gamefaqs.com/nes/587775-wizards-and-warriors/data |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101224110439/http://www.gamefaqs.com/nes/587775-wizards-and-warriors/data |archive-date=December 24, 2010 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ''Wizards & Warriors'' was Acclaim's first game as the domestic publisher; Acclaim's previous releases were all localizations of games originally released by other companies.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=To Hell and Back with Acclaim |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=40|publisher=[[Imagine Media]] |date=April 1998|page=12}}</ref> It is Rare's second NES release,<ref name=GamePro>{{cite magazine |last=Davison |first=John |title=25 Years of Rare |magazine=[[GamePro]] |date=June 2, 2010 |access-date=August 1, 2011 |url=http://www.gamepro.com/article/features/215329/25-years-of-rare/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101225180552/http://www.gamepro.com/article/features/215329/25-years-of-rare/|archive-date=2010-12-25}}</ref> after ''[[Slalom (video game)|Slalom]]''.<ref name="RG" /> The soundtrack was composed by video game composer [[David Wise (composer)|David Wise]].<ref name="GamesRadar">{{cite web |last=Elston |first=Brett |title=Music of the day: ''Wizards & Warriors'' |publisher=[[GamesRadar]] |date=June 3, 2010 |access-date=February 4, 2010 |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/game-music-of-the-day-wizards-warriors/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011045808/http://www.gamesradar.com/game-music-of-the-day-wizards-warriors/ |archive-date=October 11, 2012 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>

