''Wizards & Warriors'' was reviewed in ''[[Nintendo Fun Club News]]'', the precursor to ''[[Nintendo Power]]''.<ref name="FunClub" /> ''Nintendo Power'' called it the best game for the [[NES Advantage]] controller, allowing concentration on strategic gameplay.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=NES Advantage and NES Max | magazine=[[Nintendo Power]] |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |location=[[Redmond, WA]] |issue=3 |date=November–December 1988 |page=57 |issn=1041-9551 |oclc=18893582}}</ref> In 1989, it nominated the game for "Best Graphics & Sound" and Kuros for "Best Character" in its "Nintendo Power Awards '88", but it did not win in either category.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=''Nintendo Power'' Awards '88 | magazine=[[Nintendo Power]] |publisher=Nintendo |location=Redmond, WA |issue=5 |date=March–April 1989 |pages=91–92 |issn=1041-9551 |oclc=18893582}}</ref> ''[[VideoGames & Computer Entertainment]]'' lauded the game's challenge, the need for problem solving to use various items to defeat some enemies and make progress, the need to find hidden rooms for items, the high difficulty being offset by continues, the "excellent graphics and sound", and the arcade-style gameplay.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Plotkin |first=David |title=Video Game Reviews – ''Wizards & Warriors'' | magazine=[[VideoGames & Computer Entertainment]] |publisher=[[Larry Flynt Publications]] |location=[[Beverly Hills, CA]] |issue=4 |date=May 1989 |pages=30, 32 |issn=1059-2938 |oclc=25300986}}</ref> ''[[Power Play (magazine)|Power Play]]'' praised the graphics, sound, and extras, but criticized its "stale gameplay".<ref name="Hengst" />

Arnie Katz reviewed the game for ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'', stating that "''Wizards & Warriors'' refutes the claim that all video games are unrestrained target shoots. This engaging and well-programmed action quest offers a satisfying, well-rounded gaming experience."<ref name="CGW49">{{cite magazine |last=Katz |first=Arnie |title=Video Gaming World |magazine=Computer Gaming World |date=July 1988 |volume=1 |issue=49 |pages=44–45}}</ref>

In a retrospective of the entire ''Wizards & Warriors'' series, UK-based magazine ''[[Retro Gamer]]'' gave a positive review of the first game, saying that "Kuros's first adventure was a unique experience for NES gamers in 1987, and technically well ahead of other games for the console at the time." The review said that the platform game emphasizes hunting treasure and items, and that most gamers disliked the relatively easy difficulty level due to unlimited continues. According to the retrospective, in 1988, Rare showed ''Wizards & Warriors'' to Zippo Games, who was touring Rare and its NES library. Rare asked Zippo to develop a sequel, which became ''[[Ironsword: Wizards & Warriors II|Ironsword: Wizards & Warriors&nbsp;II]]''.<ref name="RG" /> In another retrospective at Rare's 25th anniversary, ''[[GamePro]]'' called the game "unique at the time" due to unlimited continues.<ref name="GamePro" />

''Wizards & Warriors'' has received scant coverage from modern video gaming websites. [[GamesRadar]] named the opening theme "Game music of the day", noting that the theme "suggests, from the moment you turn on the game, that knights, wizards, goblins and who knows what else are about to collide in a battle so epic it's destined for a [[Frank Frazetta|Frazetta]] painting".<ref name="GamesRadar" /> JC Fletcher from [[Joystiq]] called the game "a simple action-platformer about a guy in thick armor who kicks open treasure chests in order to bribe knights". He notes the variety of good and bad items such as the "Staff of Power" which inflicts much damage to enemies and conversely the "Cloak of Darkness", which he says "makes Kuros invisible to ''you'' but not to enemies". He said that the game has an arcade feel, with unlimited continues, a high-score list, name entry for high scores, and good music.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fletcher |first=JC |title=Virtually Overlooked: ''Wizards & Warriors'' |publisher=Joystiq |date=June 12, 2008 |access-date=February 4, 2011 |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2008/06/12/virtually-overlooked-wizards-and-warriors/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019012307/http://www.joystiq.com/2008/06/12/virtually-overlooked-wizards-and-warriors/ |archive-date=October 19, 2012 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ''[[Houston Press]]''{{'}}s Jef Rouner lauded the game's music and animation, and noted its high difficulty level, especially during boss battles.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rouner |first=Jef |title=Top 10 NES Games We're Buying This Year |newspaper=[[Houston Press]] |date=December 6, 2011 |access-date=January 2, 2012 |url=http://blogs.houstonpress.com/artattack/2011/12/top_10_nes_games_were_buying_t.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120110105959/http://blogs.houstonpress.com/artattack/2011/12/top_10_nes_games_were_buying_t.php |archive-date=January 10, 2012 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[IGN]] put ''Wizards & Warriors'' at #56 on its "Top 100 NES Games" list, and reviewer Sam Claiborn said that the game was inspired by ''[[Dungeons & Dragons]]'' style of RPGs, and added action platforming elements.<ref>{{cite web |last=Claiborn |first=Sam |title=56. ''Wizards & Warriors'' |website=IGN |access-date=February 21, 2011 |url=http://www.ign.com/top-100-nes-games/56.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091018233137/http://uk.ign.com/top-100-nes-games/56.html |archive-date=October 18, 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Seanbaby]] criticized the game for items that did not work as intended, including the "Cloak of Darkness" and the "Boots of Lava Walk".<ref>{{cite web |title=Useless Power-Ups |publisher=[[Seanbaby]] |access-date=February 4, 2011 |url=http://www.seanbaby.com/nes/useless.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110105040818/http://www.seanbaby.com/nes/useless.htm |archive-date=January 5, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>

==Other media==
''Wizards & Warriors'' was published as a standalone handheld game by Acclaim in September&nbsp;1989, in a series of handheld ports including ''[[WWF WrestleMania Challenge]]'', ''[[Knight Rider (video game)|Knight Rider]]'', ''[[1943: The Battle of Midway]]'', and ''[[Rocky (1987 video game)|Rocky]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Acclaim Takes Games in Hand |magazine=VideoGames & Computer Entertainment |publisher=Larry Flynt Publications |location=Beverly Hills, CA |issue=8 |date=September 1989 |page=14 |issn=1059-2938 |oclc=25300986}}</ref> Kuros and Malkil were featured – along with the title characters from ''[[Kwirk]]'' and ''[[BigFoot (video game)|BigFoot]]'', Tyrone from ''[[Arch Rivals]]'', and characters from ''[[NARC (video game)|NARC]]'' – in the 1990 animated series ''[[The Power Team (TV series)|The Power Team]]'', part of the video game reviewing show ''[[Video Power]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Power team'' |publisher=RetroJunk.com |access-date=February 3, 2011 |url=http://www.retrojunk.com/details_tvshows/1497-power-team/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090329033128/http://www.retrojunk.com/details_tvshows/1497-power-team/ |archive-date=2009-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=News Bits – Video Characters to Star on TV |magazine=[[VideoGames & Computer Entertainment]] |issue=16 |date=May 1990 |page=18 |publisher=[[Larry Flynt Publications]] |location=[[Beverly Hills, CA]] |issn=1059-2938 |oclc=25300986}}</ref> Malkil is in an episode of ''[[Captain N: The Game Master]]'' called "Nightmare on Mother Brain's Street" where the game world is referred to as Excalibur and not Elrond.

''Wizards & Warriors'' is one of the eight NES games novelized for the ''[[Worlds of Power]]'' series, written by children's book author [[Ellen Miles]] (series' creator [[Seth Godin]] is also credited under the pseudonym "F. X. Nine").<ref name="WorldsofPower1">{{cite web |url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=3&cId=3152540 |title=8-Bit Lit: Inside the NES' ''Worlds of Power'' Series |last1=Struck |first1=Shawn |last2=Sharkey |first2=Scott |date=August 8, 2006 |access-date=February 4, 2011 |website=[[1UP.com]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605020331/http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=3&cId=3152540 |archive-date=June 5, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Nine |first1=F. X. |author-link=Seth Godin |last2=Miles |first2=Ellen |title=Wizards & Warriors |publisher=[[Scholastic Corporation]] |date=July 1990 |location=New York, NY |isbn=978-0-590-43769-1 |oclc=22581353}}</ref>

